@REM What is Murks Good for ?


@NODE ABOUT "What is Murks ?"
@{LINE}
Murks IDE is a free Integrated Development Environment.
At this Moment it is very limited, but it's goal is to become
a real IDE like AmiDevCpp (Windows).
@{LINE}
Murks offers you a comfortable Environvent to create Applications for AROS,
on AROS.
@{LINE}
It comes completely with everything you need to start Development.
@{LINE}
Murks uses the AmiDevCpp Project-File-Format,
so you can exchange your Projects between Windows and AROS.
@{LINE}
So what can you do with Murks, right now ?
@{LINE}
@{LINE}
@{JCENTER}

@{B}You can load AmiDevCpp Projects.@{UB}

@{B}You can save AmiDevCpp Projects.@{UB}

@{B}You can create new Projects.@{UB}

@{B}You can edit this Projects.@{UB}

@{B}You can add Files to a Project.@{UB}

@{B}You can change the options for the Compiler and the Linker.@{UB}

@{B}You can compile your Projects.@{UB}

@{B}You can run your Projects.@{UB}

@ENDNODE


@REM How to Install


@NODE INSTALL "Installing Murks"
@{JCENTER}
@{LINE}
The Installation could'nt be simpler...
@{LINE}
Just extract the Archive to your Harddrive.

@ENDNODE


@NODE START "Getting started..."
@{JCENTER}
@{LINE}
Start Murks! from the Shell. NOT by DoubleClick !
@{LINE}
The Shell will display the compiler errors.
@{LINE}
1. Just Click on "Open Project".
@{LINE}
2. Browse to the "Examples" Drawer.
@{LINE}
3. Choose one of the Examples (#?.dev).
@{LINE}
4. The Example Project will be loaded.
@{LINE}
5. On the left Side, you can choose one of the Project's Files. 
   @{LINE}
   The one you click, will be displayed and can can be edited.
@{LINE}
6. Click on "Save Project". Make sure you choose a directory and not just a Drive !
@{LINE}
7. Click on "Build Project". The Project will be compiled.
@{LINE}
8. Click on "Run" and the new created executable will be started.
@{LINE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE POPTIONS "Change Project Options"
@{JCENTER}
@{LINE}
When You develop new Applications, you often have to link to a Library and change some Compiler Options.
@{LINE}
With Murks, this a comfortable thing.
@{LINE}
Just open the Menu "Project"->"Project Options".
@{LINE}
A Dialog appears. On the Left side you see the Compiler Options,
@{LINE}
on the right side the Linker Options. You can select a Option and click "Remove"
@{LINE}
to remove it, or you enter a Option in the String Gadget and Click "Add" and the new Options will appear
@{LINE} 
in the List.
@{LINE}
You have to click "Proceed" to Apply Changes or "Abort" to leace the Dialog without taking the Changes effect.
@{LINE}
@{LINE}
The Syntax of the Compiler and Linker Options is just the same as if your start gcc from commandline.
@{LINE}
So if you want to compile a ZUNE Program, add "-lmui" to Linker Options.
@{LINE}
See Example Projects for more Info.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ADDF "Adding source Files"
@{JCENTER}
@{LINE}
You can add Files, by simply clicking on Add File to Project.
@{LINE}
A Dialog appears and you have to enter a Filename.
@{LINE}
Make sure you enter the complete File Name like test.c or test.h
@{LINE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE BUGS "Know Problems"
@{JCENTER}
@{LINE}
As this is Beta Software, there are a few Problems.
@{LINE}
One Problem are Path's without subdirectorys.
@{LINE}
A Project saved directly in "RAM:" will not compile.
@{LINE}
A Project saved in "RAM:MyDir" will!
@{LINE}
Remove file from a Project is not possible yet.
@{LINE}
Compiler Errors are not displayed in the "Compiler Output".
@{LINE}
There is no C++ Compiler yet. C++ Project wont work!
@{LINE}
Start MurksIDE from a Shell, and the errors will be displayed there.
@{LINE}
If you really need to remove a file, then you have to edit your .dev File manually.
@{LINE}
If you are working on a Project and then want to work on another one,
@{LINE}
then you have to quit and restart Murks first.
@{LINE}
Dont use -o Options to change the Output Filename !
@{LINE}
More to come...
@{LINE}
@ENDNODE

